%I A290177 #25 Apr 08 2026 10:55:40
%S A290177 18,88916,1147805,6042955,761357755,1161183643
%N A290177 Bases b for which there exists an integer y such that y^3 in base b consists of three identical digits.
%C A290177 A number b is a term if 1+b+b^2 can be multiplied by a number k < b to obtain a cube. The smallest candidate k can be easily obtained from the prime factorization of 1+b+b^2. For example, for b = 761357755 we have 1+b+b^2 = 3 * 7^2 * 2131 * 12277^3, so k = 3^2 * 7 * 2131^2, which happens to smaller than b.  a(7) > 10^10. - _Giovanni Resta_, Sep 02 2019
%C A290177 From _Bert Dobbelaere_, Apr 07 2026: (Start)
%C A290177 If b is a term, then b^2+b+1 cannot be cubefree. We can factor it uniquely as b^2+b+1 = u * v^2 * w^3 where u*v is squarefree. Then b is a term iff k = u^2*v < b. Suppose w=1, then k^2 < b^2 < b^2+b+1 would imply u^4*v^2 < u*v^2, which is impossible for positive u and v.
%C A290177 a(7) > 2*10^11. (End)
%D A290177 Andrew Bridy, Robert J. Lemke Oliver, Arlo Shallit, and Jeffrey Shallit, The Generalized Nagell-Ljunggren Problem: Powers with Repetitive Representations, Experimental Math, 28 (2019), 428-439.
%H A290177 Andrew Bridy, Robert J. Lemke Oliver, Arlo Shallit, and Jeffrey Shallit, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1707.03894">The Generalized Nagell-Ljunggren Problem: Powers with Repetitive Representations</a>, preprint, arXiv:1707.03894 [math.NT], July 14 2017.
%e A290177 For example, for b = 18, we have y = 7, and the base-b representation of y^3 is 111.
%Y A290177 Cf. A290172, A290173, A290176, A290185.
%K A290177 nonn,base,more,changed
%O A290177 1,1
